uding linalool and ocimene were detected as early as 6.00 a.m., reaching the highest level at 12.00-2.00 p.m., but reduced drastically after 4.00 p.m. We postulated that scent emission of floral tissues of VMP, especially in the petal and sepal, was closely associated with the effect of temperature whereby the highest level of sunlight coincided with the highest level of volatile emission while none of the fragrance compounds were detected at night probably due to the lower temperature as well as the inactivity of respective pollinators. Contrary to fragrance emission, the level of fragrance relative transcripts was much higher at night than during daytime (Fig. 6c) as observed also in our previous studies on VMP [CITATION_9] ."
